<div id="review_2227184624" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2227184624" />
    <a title="Bill Leach" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18293816-bill-leach"><img alt="Bill Leach" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2227184624?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bill Leach" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bill Leach" href="/user/show/18293816-bill-leach">Bill Leach</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2227184624" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer75242432865042913">The 1996-1997 Vendée Globe is examined in some detail by Lundy, who himself is a sailor. This race for single-handed boats starts and ends in France, going south through the Atlantic and around Antarctica. The book describes the boats and what makes the high latitude sailing different from other kinds of ocean sailing. The wide, light boats are designed to plan on the long waves typical of the southern oceans.<br/><br/>The skippers are the primary focus of the narrative, providing good insights into their</span>
  <span id="freeText75242432865042913" style="display:none">The 1996-1997 Vendée Globe is examined in some detail by Lundy, who himself is a sailor. This race for single-handed boats starts and ends in France, going south through the Atlantic and around Antarctica. The book describes the boats and what makes the high latitude sailing different from other kinds of ocean sailing. The wide, light boats are designed to plan on the long waves typical of the southern oceans.<br /><br />The skippers are the primary focus of the narrative, providing good insights into their feelings and outlook during the race.<br /><br />The book has little on the day-to-day sailing activities and the feel of sailing on these wild oceans. Rather the concentration is on the accidents, how they played out, and the skipper's thoughts on them.<br /><br />Lundy explores the forces that drive sailors to undertake such dangerous adventures. He notes that after such extreme adventures, people often find normal life rather tame and eventually want to start the next trip, regardless of the dangers. As Lundy shows, this effect is found not only in sailing, but extreme mountaineering and other such sports.<br /><br />The book has little on the day-to-day sailing activities and the feel of sailing on these wild oceans. Rather the concentration is on the accidents, how they played out, and the skipper's thoughts on them. He notes that Bernard Moitessier was the ultimate sailor who sailed for the aesthetics of the sport, and implies that is where one should go to understand the beauty of sailing.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="75242432865042913" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


